node.text: Jeff and Jared are back at it again with a MTB dropper post buyer’s guide. This time the boys walk us through the buying process and everything you need to know about buying the right mountain bike dropper seatpost for your bike. With a wide variety of choices out there it can be a daunting task. First the guys share a brief history of dropper posts. Next they go into a breakdown of the somewhat complicated topic of dropper post sizing which includes the diameter, total length, insertion depth, as well as travel options. Another thing to consider is the lever type, which includes how the cable mounts to the lever itself as well as the clamp style. We then share some of our favorite brands and models like @oneupcomponents, @ridefoxbike, @raceface, @rockshox, @pnwcomponents, and @bikeyoke. Finally they give some final thoughts on buying advice and service intervals. Check it out!

node.title: Dropper Post Buyer's Guide | Everything You Need To Know

You know what time of the month it is... It's time for our next round of Trending Mountain Bike Products! This time around @jeffcayley is back in the studio with @jaredbeerman to go over some really useful products that gained a lot of popularity in July for 2021. Starting us off is a pin replacement kit for the @raceface Chester Flat Pedals. Next up is the @parktoolblue PCS-10.3 Home Repair Stand for anyone looking to wrench down on their bikes at home. From there we go over the very popular @rockshox Zeb / Domain Short Bolt-On MTB Fender. This thing is essential for keeping debris and animal droppings from flying up and hitting you in the face out on the trail. For anyone without a Zeb or Domain, we do go over some of our own WC Fenders that you can put on virtually any fork with a few zip ties. Next up is the @maxxisbike Aggressor Tire. Most of us here at the shop run this as a rear tire quite often as it offers the perfect balance between rolling speed and grip. Next up is our new MTB jerseys! We just dropped three new short sleeve jerseys to keep you cool while riding in those summer months. Jeff also introduces our new @ketlmtn Warmweather Socks which were created to keep your feet cool, no matter how hot it gets. Least but not last is the Rockshox Debonair C1 Air Spring Upgrade. This little guy helps keep your fork running smoothly and can even help fix a travel issue if your current Rockshox Fork is sitting lower than it should be. So sit back, grab your favorite beverage and enjoy! Hit the link in our bio to check out the entire article!

We are back with @ma651 for another bike check. This time, however, we are going over his custom painted @yeticycles SB150. You might recognize this bike as we did a feature on it last year but Matt has made some changes to the bike so we decided to give it another bike check to check it out. Peep the build list down below:
 
Frame: @yeticycles SB150 painted by @airtrix
Suspension: @ridefoxbike Factory 38 Fork, Float X2 Rear Shock, Transfer Dropper
Drivetrain: @srammtb XX1 Eagle AXS in Rainbow
Wheels: @chriskingbuzz hubs laced to @dtswiss rims
Tires: @maxxisbike Assegai and DHR II
Cockpit: @renthalcycling Apex Stem, Fatbar Handlebars

node.text:
We are back with yet another Trending MTB Products video for the month of June for 2021. This time we focus a lot more on the smaller items that have gained popularity over the past month. Starting us off, @jaredbeerman and @ask_liam go over some items from @mucoff. Their Bio Dry Chain Lube and No Puncture Hassle Tire Sealant are great items to stock up on for the summer months, especially with the heatwave we are currently experiencing all over the country. From there the boys get into the @stansnotubes Dart Tool, a tubeless tire plug in case you slash open your tire out on the trail and need to quickly seal it to make it back home. No one likes being stranded in the middle of nowhere. Next up is what we would consider to be the most popular product we sell, the @dtswiss 54t Ratchet kit. This upgrade allows you to increase the engagement on your rear hub for faster pickup speeds around corners and technical climbs. We also go over two incredible bikes from @mondrakerbikes. The F-Podium Carbon DC R is a downcountry machine ready to tackle the longest rides imaginable and the Superfoxy Carbon R which is about as enduro as you can get! With a lot of travel and 29" wheels, The Superfoxy has proven to be one of the faster bikes on the market. Last but not least, the boys go over some ergonomic items for storing essential mountain bike tools and water on your bike. The @lezyneofficial Flow Side Loader Bottle Cage helps store a bottle on your frame and has a unique side load design that works with some of the tightest frames on the market. The Worldwide Cyclery @backcountryresearchstraps Mutherload Frame Strap also helps riders carry an extra tube, C02, and any MTB tools you may need on your bike which helps you keep your pockets empty and keeps a backpack off your back. It also features our custom topographical design and logo to help you support the greatest bike shop on earth. So sit back, relax, and give’er a watch! You might find something you actually need! For more info, hit the link in our bio!

Upgrading your Mountain Bike's Handlebars can be confusing! There are so many different sizes to choose from. What does a handlebar's rise do? What is backsweep? Upsweep? Is carbon really better than alloy? How wide do my bars need to be? And so on and so on. There is a lot to think about and that is exactly why @JeffCayley wanted to sit down and go over everything you should know when upgrading your MTB Handlebars. So sit back, crack a cold one and enjoy! If you are still confused on what handlebar to get even after watching this whole video, just give us a call! Our squad of cyborg bike nerds are here ready to help!

node.text:
Upgrading the rear shock on your mountain bikes is one of the best and most noticeable ways to change the feel and performance of your bike. When looking to upgrade your bike's rear shock, there are a few key elements to know and consider. Things like shock length, stroke, and eye to eye measurements are crucial to know before you make any kind of change. Also, consider if you want a coil shock or an air shock. Both have their advantages and disadvantages. Not to mention which brand to choose from - there are countless options from Fox, RockShox, Push, Cane Creek, and more. Sounds like a lot...it is. Thankfully, @Jeffcayley and @jaredbeerman are here to explain everything you need to know about upgrading your MTB rear suspension. Get a notepad out because this episode is loaded with good information. Enjoy!

The new @RockShox Domain fork is the perfect step in the right direction. With the release of the ZEB and Fox 38 in 2020, we saw a lot of effort go into these beefier enduro forks. The downfall was their expensive costs. This is no longer an issue as RockShox has produced a more affordable 38mm stanchion fork that can still take any punch you throw at it. With a motion control RC damper, debonair air spring, torque cap compatibility, and a travel range of 150mm-180mm for both 29" and 27.5" wheel sizes, the RockShox Domain offers some of the same great features we see on their Ultimate line for only a fraction of the cost. Is this the right fork for you? Hit play and find out!

@jaredbeerman is in the house today with all the details on the new @ridefoxbike 2022 suspension updates which include the revised Fox 34 & Fox 34 Step-Cast fork, along with the  Float X, and DHX rear shock. A lot has changed when it comes to the Fox 34, but most importantly, it is lighter and stiffer! Touching on the rear shocks, the DPX2 is no more and has now been replaced with the Float X. And if a coil rear shock is how you like to party, then the new DHX coil shock will be just what you want. There’s a lot of new MTB suspension to cover in this episode so grab a carrot juice and enjoy!

On today's MTB Podcast, @jeffcayley, @ask_liam, and @jaredbeerman dive into some listener questions with topics around tire insert technology, riding with poop on your bike, ideas for MTB innovations as well as current supply chain issues and pricing increases. The boys also recap their recent trip to Colorado. Some of the finer points of the trip were visiting the guys at @revelbikes as well as some night time shenanigans with the crew. While in Colorado they got together with @chasingepicmtb to hit some epic trails in Crested Butte. Then they roll into some interesting stories of recent antics which include the Worldwide Cyclery Mammoth Lakes trip and Jeff's brutal half marathon. Enjoy!

node.text: Jeff and Jared are back at it again with a MTB dropper post buyer’s guide. This time the boys walk us through the buying process and everything you need to know about buying the right mountain bike dropper seatpost for your bike. With a wide variety of choices out there it can be a daunting task. First the guys share a brief history of dropper posts. Next they go into a breakdown of the somewhat complicated topic of dropper post sizing which includes the diameter, total length, insertion depth, as well as travel options. Another thing to consider is the lever type, which includes how the cable mounts to the lever itself as well as the clamp style. We then share some of our favorite brands and models like @oneupcomponents, @ridefoxbike, @raceface, @rockshox, @pnwcomponents, and @bikeyoke. Finally they give some final thoughts on buying advice and service intervals. Check it out!
